title.narrative: OUTPUT 3.2 HEALTH QUALITY

description.narrative: By 2024, health sector policy, plans and budgets use solid evidence to strengthen the health system for child and maternal survival., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024: Significantly more girls, boys, adolescents and women, especially those who are marginalized and/or living in humanitarian conditions, have access to and utilize evidence-based, high-impact quality maternal, neonatal, child, adolescent health, and HIV interventions.

description.narrative: UNICEF continued to support provision of RMNCAH health services, with 170,302 pregnant women and 1,008,789 children under 5 accessing care. Uptake of routine immunizations declined as a result of emergencies and strong focus on introducing the new nOPV, COVID-19 and typhoid conjugate vaccines. Some 853,279 and 978,333 children aged 0–59 months were reached in the first and second nOPV rounds, respectively. Some 1,524,706 children aged 9 months to 15 years were reached during one round of typhoid vaccine. The cold chain system was strengthened. There was a decline in Community Health service delivery and reporting due to funding constraints. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:25/01/2022
